# Agent Instructions

This project is an Intropy **loader block**: a .NET worker that subscribes to a
system topic and loads the events into an external system through an outbound
connector. It is one component of an integration system; the edges between
components are declared in a sibling SystemHost project, not here.

## Project overview

- Framework: .NET 10, ASP.NET Minimal API worker
- Block kind: loader
- App id / component name: `{{ .name }}`
- Subscribes: topic `{{ .subscribesTopic }}`
- Loads into: external system `{{ .targetSystem }}` via the `{{ .connectorName | default .targetSystem }}` connector (transport chosen at `intropy system create`)

## Scaffold record

`.intropy/scaffold.json` carries this component's edge intent in its `topology`
section (block kind, subscriptions, connectors). `intropy system create`
reads the records of all sibling components to generate a wired SystemHost —
do not edit the `topology` section by hand; re-scaffold instead.

## Runtime contract

The SystemHost's run backend starts this worker with:

- `INTROPY__COMPONENT` — the component name.
- `INTROPY__CONFIG` — path to `{{ .name }}.intropy.json`, the generated runtime
  config carrying the component's subscriptions and connector bindings
  (including the pub/sub component name, which is a system-level decision made
  by the SystemHost).

The folder name, csproj name, and Dapr app-id must all stay `{{ .name }}` —
the SystemHost resolves this project by that convention (`../{{ .name }}/{{ .name }}.csproj`).

## Wiring into a system

From the parent directory that holds all component folders:

```bash
intropy system create -n <system-name>
```

Then validate the topology:

```bash
dotnet run --project <SystemName>.SystemHost -- check
```
